                    <span>It's about time someone write about the growing problem in California, especially Southern California. Most people who call this text or others like it racist are dead wrong. Racism, like communism before it, is a red-herring. I grew up in Southern California. Drive through East Los Angeles and tell me how you feel when you see the Mexican Flag flying high. It makes you wonder if many Hispanics have an agenda. In Santa Ana the common language is Spanish. Assimilation into American life is obviously not working. This text raises honest concerns. A book to accompany this would be Alien Nation by Peter Brimelow. As a side note Mexicans didn't exist until the Spanish colonized the "New World". Spanish was brought to the Americas by Spaniards. It never existed in the "New World" before their arrival. It's as foreign as it can get.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">"New arrivals"? Hardly.</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>2</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>2</span>
                      /
                      <span>6</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2004-07-02</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>While I'm sure the author is NOT a racist, many of the rave reviewers of his book on this site seem to be ("bronze tide!?!" Good Lord!). Something to consider--what's lost in all of this is the fact that many of the areas of the US in question--in particular, California, the Southwest, and Texas--have long histories of latino and indigenous presence dating from before anglo settlers arrived. A conflict or two fought on dubious pretexts gave this country legal dominion over those territories, but hardly gives us the right to blithely talk about the "newcomers" to "our" land. There are Spanish-speaking families who have lived in the San Joaquin valley for generations, since before the war--it seems a bit rich to call them "foreigners" when they speak the language they always have. And there are the descendents of folks who left those parts during times of conflict and are now coming back. And there are economic refugees fleeing a country whose problems might have more than a little to do with the fact that said country lost half of its national territory in a war with the US as it was attempting to enter modernity, or that millions of its citizens work in low-wage, non-union American factories run by businesses who don't like all the crazy perks that greedy American workers demand--health care, a pension, a living wage etc. The names of the places tell a story too--Los Angeles, San Antonio, San Diego. There's a more complicated history to be considered--and "immigrant" might not be as good a term to use as "returning refugee". Something to think about.</span>
                  
              
